s survivors. Murphy investigates how infantrymen and civilians attempted to make sense of the war while it was still in progress by reviving the picaresque, a literary mode in which unheroic protagonists are forced to fend for themselves in a chaotic and hostile world. By examining works by French and European novelists, journalists, graphic artists, cultural critics, and filmmakers-including Charlie Chaplin-Libby Murphy shows how the rich tradition of the European picaresque was uniquely appropriate for expressing anxieties provoked by modern, industrialized warfare.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Feb 2020) 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xLiterature and the war. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xMotion pictures and the war. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xSocial aspectszFrance. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zFrancexLiterature and the war. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2016z978311066771440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300225006423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300225006.jpg  a978-3-11-066771-4  YUP eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aEBA_FAO